      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i'll dig into the transition logic. but it's just so frustrating because it feels like it's sabotaging us. we fix one thing and then something else just breaks out of nowhere. it's like the system is actively resisting these fixes. is there anything else besides code bugs that could cause this kind of erratic behavior? maybe some weird environmental factor?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While code bugs are common culprits, environmental factors like transient network latency issues between your application and the database, or memory pressure causing unpredictable garbage collection pauses, can also trigger these erratic failures. Sometimes, a background service like a log aggregator or a monitoring tool might temporarily consume resources, creating a \"noisy neighbor\" effect that disrupts critical transactions without showing up in standard load metrics. Additionally, if your transaction locking mechanism relies on a specific hardware or network configuration, subtle changes in that infrastructure could introduce race conditions that only appear under specific timing windows. It's often helpful to review infrastructure metrics like CPU utilization per core, network packet loss rates, and memory fragmentation over time to rule out these hidden environmental stressors.",
